    |F(omega)|^2 = 147:   12 tournaments  (= 2^2 + 2*11 + 11^2)
    |F(omega)|^2 = 151:   10 tournaments  (= 5^2 + 5*9 + 9^2)
    |F(omega)|^2 = 171:    2 tournaments  (= 6^2 + 6*9 + 9^2)
    |F(omega)|^2 = 193:   10 tournaments  (= 7^2 + 7*9 + 9^2)
    |F(omega)|^2 = 243:    2 tournaments  (= 9^2 + 9*9 + 9^2)

======================================================================
PART 9: H vs EISENSTEIN NORM — THE CONSTRAINT SURFACE
======================================================================

  Given H = G0 + G1 + G2 and N = (G0-G2)^2 + (G0-G2)(G1-G2) + (G1-G2)^2:

  Let s = G0+G1+G2 = H, and set u = G0-G2, v = G1-G2.
  Then G2 = (s - u - v) / 3 ... wait, G0 = G2+u, G1 = G2+v.
  So s = G2+u + G2+v + G2 = 3*G2 + u + v.
  Thus G2 = (s - u - v)/3.

  For G2 >= 0: u + v <= s = H.
  For G0 >= 0: G2 + u >= 0, so u >= -(s-u-v)/3, so 4u+v >= -s... always true for u,v small.

  The norm N = u^2 + uv + v^2.

  Given H, the MAXIMUM possible norm is achieved when the G_j are
  as UNBALANCED as possible.

  If one G_j = H and others = 0: u = H, v = 0 (say), N = H^2.
  If perfectly balanced: G0=G1=G2=H/3, u=v=0, N=0.

  So 0 <= N <= H^2, with N=0 iff H divisible by 3 and balanced.

  The constraint is: (H, N) must be ACHIEVABLE by some tournament.
  
  n=5: Achievable (H, Eisenstein_norm) pairs:
    H=  1: norms = [1, 3]
    H=  3: norms = [1, 7, 9, 27]
    H=  5: norms = [1, 3, 4, 7, 12, 13, 21, 25, 37, 75]
    H=  9: norms = [4, 7, 9, 13, 27, 28, 31, 61, 63, 73, 109]
    H= 11: norms = [7, 12, 13, 16, 21, 37, 39, 43, 75, 79, 111, 127, 129, 193]
    H= 13: norms = [7, 12, 13, 25, 28, 31, 48, 49, 52, 57, 91, 93, 97, 147, 151]
    H= 15: norms = [9, 19, 27, 36, 108, 109, 117, 171, 243]

  H=7 is forbidden: NO (7, N) pair exists for ANY N!
  This means no partition of 7 into (G0, G1, G2) is achievable.

======================================================================
DONE — EISENSTEIN NORM OF F-POLYNOMIAL
======================================================================
